# Quick Start

### Load the library
```html
<script type="module">
import 'https://cdn.jsdelivr.net/gh/un-zynq/zynq-lib@0.3.2/index.min.js';
await ZYNQ.load('peer');
</script>
```

### Simple mode (recommended)
```javascript
const engine = new ZYNQ.peer({
  video: false,
  audio: false,
  txt: true
});

engine.on('ready', id => {
  console.log('My ID:', id);
});

engine.on('data', msg => {
  console.log('Received:', msg);
});
```

### Connect & send
```javascript
engine.connect('remote-peer-id');
engine.send('hello world');
```

# Messaging

### Send message
```javascript
engine.send('Hello world');
engine.send({ type: 'chat', text: 'Hi' }); // objects are supported by PeerJS
```

### Receive
```javascript
engine.on('data', msg => {
  console.log('Received from peer:', msg);
});
```

**Security**
- Only strings pass by default (non-string payloads are silently rejected)
- Automatic rate limiting (30 msgs/sec per connection)
- Messages larger than 64KB are rejected

# Media (Audio & Video)

### Connect with media
```javascript
engine.connect(remoteId); // uses config set at creation
// or when creating:
new ZYNQ.peer({ video: true, audio: true });
```

### Handle streams
```javascript
engine.on('localStream', stream => {
  localVideo.srcObject = stream;
});

engine.on('stream', remoteStream => {
  remoteVideo.srcObject = remoteStream;
});
```

**Stream Management**
- Single shared `getUserMedia` call across the entire library
- Streams are cached and reused automatically
- Automatic cleanup on `close()` / `destroy()`
